metadata.name: Paper Mandala #63
metadata.description:
A collaboration with P1xelboy and Paper Buddha.
Beautiful paper mandalas made purely with code in Paper Buddha's style.
Features include:
27 different palettes
3 different mandala types (Lotus, Starburst Style 1 and Starburst Style 2)
Four sections of the mandala with one of 10 different pattern types (Dots, Checks, Crosses, Triangles, Stripes, Circles, Polygons, Lazers, Quadrants and Hatching)
4 different direction types of shadow - of varying length
Randomly placed star background
Randomly placed Nebula
Possible Special Pattern Effect with darker stippling pattern
Possible Nirvana Effect where random colors are added to one of either Golden, Silver, Bronze, Blue Moon or Sea Green palettes.

Using only code, this produces a unique output which does take a few seconds to load.
Press "S" to Save your unique Paper Mandala as a 2048 x 2048 JPG
Press "R" for a random shuffle effect - (please wait for reload) - Refresh page to reset

The project works in a responsive browser, so to set up for phone background or watch, resize the browser accordingly and Alt + Print Screen to get an appropriately sized image.

Offered as a Dutch Auction, holders of the first 20 tokens (1-20) will receive additional benefits in the form of utility for future releases in the P1xelboy/Paper Mandala collaboration series. (exact details to be determined)
This utility will remain attached to tokens 1-20 and transfer to the new owner upon subsequent secondary sales.

Uses p5.js and p5.pattern
@p1x3lboy @paperbuddha - September 2022

metadata.name: simple things #26
metadata.description:
There‚Äôs beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing ‚Äúd‚Äù followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press ‚Äúd 0‚Äù and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.

metadata.name: Dencity #875
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Take Wing #67
metadata.description:
‚ÄúTake Wing‚Äù is a generative art collection depicting the hope, optimism, and thrilling excitement of a person taking off, gaining traction, and soaring to new heights and off into the great unknown.  

The algorithm behind the piece stems from an attempt to go back to art fundamentals and codify composition rules and painterly techniques into a generative form - taking into account focal points, contrast, eye movement, and color theory while still giving the algorithm freedom to explore random color palettes, random flow field movement, random brush strokes, and many other degrees of freedom.

The collection is made in pure code with p5.js and a few GLSL fragment shaders.

The piece has been created to be exhibited at "In Touch" with VerticalCryptoArt in Berlin in September 2022, curated by Anika Meier.

------------------------------------------------

To get a (somewhat) high-resolution output, open the live view of your token, and then edit the URL adding &h=5400 at the end of it.  5400 is the tallest you can go, but you can also put a smaller number if you desire.  Be aware that this will only work on a machine with a very beefy GPU, and even then may take a bit, so please be patient!

metadata.name: Sparsely Populated Grid #256
metadata.description:
‚ÄúSparsely Populated Grid‚Äù is the result of an architect‚Äôs fascination with Cartographies and a crypto-enthusiast love for Neo Punk aesthetics. The first sketch, drawn by hand with Procreate, was made in October 2021.

This is an exploration on the field of Generative Cartographies, an abstract diagrammatic representation of a randomly generated area within the virtual IPFS world. Everything starts with an GRID of varying sizes and angles, subsequently POPULATED by a random number of forms. But, how to populate the grid? SPARSELY, of course, with just the right amount of superpositions.

The algorithm produces varying compositions of fourteen different forms, with seven possible mixes and ten colour palettes. Movement, made possible by its generative digital nature, follows sinusoidal patterns, as if the forms breathed and danced to an unheard music.

Besides, they never forget to celebrate birthdays.


// INTERACTIVITY

- CLICK or SPACEBAR to stop movement.
- UP and DOWN ARROWS to Disable/Enable graphic elements such as texts (wink).
- LEFT and RIGHT ARROWS (when stopped) to Move frames back and forth.
- Press 1 for a low-res PNG.
- Press 2 for a medium-res PNG (3x).
- Press 3 for a hi-res PNG (6x).
- Press G for Glitch (low-res).
- Press P for PixelArt (low-res).

If you want a different resolution, you can also add ?&res=xxx to the url to get your desired output. Then simply Right-Click SAVE the canvas -- experimental
